Introduction: The Wuhan Cultural and Tourism Administration also said that 4,096 Wuhan tourists are still outside the country.

By Chen Shanshan

Because of the Spring Festival and the impact of the epidemic, Wuhan Mayor Zhou Xianwang said today at a news conference on the prevention and control of the COVID-19 infection held by the Government of the People's Republic of China on the evening of the 26th, more than five million people have left Wuhan, with nine million remaining in the city.

According to the first financial previously disclosed flight big data, of these 5 million people, many are flying to travel abroad. There are currently 4,096 Wuhan tourists abroad, the Wuhan Culture and Tourism Bureau said today.

So how has the rest of the world responded to the epidemic, while everyone else has responded? First Financial reporter through the site interviews and authoritative information to comb:

Thailand

Thailand is currently the country with the highest number of confirmed cases of new type pneumonia, with a total of 4 cases. This can also be related to the departure data from Wuhan in the past month: 12.30-1.22 international departure data from Wuhan Airlines show that, to Bangkok airport in Thailand, the number one seat.

At present, due to the cancellation of all flights at Wuhan Airport, many returning Wuhan tourists have been caught up in the embarrassment of not being able to return home and the 15-day landing visa is about to expire.

However, in view of the fact that the landing visa is about to expire, the Thai government and the Immigration Bureau issued a notice yesterday, regarding the closure of certain airports in China due to the new type of pneumonia epidemic, resulting in some Chinese tourists returning home but remaining in Thailand, a waiver of the penalty for the anticipated stay will be imposed and an extension of the stay will be applied.

The Thai side stressed that the announcement was limited to cities such as Wuhan and Huanggang in Hubei Province.

| Singapore

Singapore is also one of the main destinations for Wuhan residents to go abroad. The number of seats from Wuhan to Singapore is second after Bangkok, Thailand. Three cases have been confirmed in Singapore so far.

At present, there have been in Singapore to end the tour of Wuhan passengers, re-booked to other flights back home, landing in Hubei Province outside the city.

SINGAPORE-BASED COOLAIR, for example, said in a statement on the 25th that it offered the option of a full refund and later re-booking to other cities due to the cancellation of flights to Wuhan, and eventually rebooked 116 wuhan-based passengers on flight TR188 to Hangzhou.

At 10:00 on the 24th, TR188 arrived at Hangzhou Xiaoshan International Airport from Singapore, but there were 219 other cities on the flight in addition to 116 Wuhan guests. According to an epidemic report from the Hangzhou City Prevention and control headquarters, due to prior information, after the plane landed, two people with fever were immediately sent to the Xiaoshan District First People's Hospital, while the rest of the Wuhan passengers were quarantined at the airport hotel, the 219 other passengers were also left under medical observation at the Party School of the Municipal Party Committee.

According to our reporter's understanding, at around 0:40 on January 26, another suspected case of new-type pneumonia was found on flight TR134 from Singapore to Xi'an. At present, the patient has been treated at a designated hospital, and 35 passengers on the flight have also been medically observed, the remaining 99 people (including the flight crew) are still being asked to go to the designated hotel for inspection.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
| Japan

The city's third-largest port of call was Narita International Airport, where three cases have also been confirmed, with the first fully recovered and the last two still being treated in Tokyo hospitals.

Japan's Prime Minister, Shinz Abe, confirmed at a budget meeting of the Lower House of parliament on the morning of January 27 that the Japanese cabinet would include new pneumonia as a "designated infectious disease" at a meeting on January 28, this means that the Japanese government can take advice to patients, compulsory hospital treatment, employment restrictions and other measures. In Japan, if they are forced to be hospitalized, all treatment costs will be borne by the government, regardless of nationality.

At home, the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Japan has issued a "level 2 infection risk alert" , asking Japanese nationals not to travel to Wuhan and Hubei except in case of emergency, and asking all Japanese in China, register your personal information at Chinese diplomatic and consular missions in case you get help in the first place.

From the 23rd, Japan suspended all flights to Wuhan, Japan's major enterprises canceled staff to Wuhan and Hubei Business Trip plans.

In addition, the Japanese government has launched an emergency epidemic prevention mechanism, designated major infectious disease treatment hospitals near major airports, equipped with special equipment, and the airport epidemic prevention agencies have also carried out transfer training after the discovery of infected persons.

First financial reporter also saw in Kansai Region Airport, the airport entry infrared temperature detector, and to every Chinese entry into a "health advisory notice" , if there is a problem can be consulted at the relevant health care.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
It is worth noting that so far, the Japanese government has not restricted the entry of tourists from Wuhan to Japan. Instead, free hand sanitizers have been placed in front of hotels, restaurants and department stores where Chinese tourists tend to be concentrated.

First Finance reporter also saw in some Japanese cosmetic shops that there are few respirators left that have the function of anti-virus, but the staff would still take the initiative to introduce the reasons for the different efficacy and price of each kind of respirator, a few days ago, some Japanese shops also reduced the price of face masks and wrote "China refuels" , but these days, many Japanese pharmacies also began to limit the purchase of face masks for tourists, because "inventory is running short" .

There are more Japanese private enterprises, donated 100 million anti-epidemic masks to China, the current batch of masks have reached Chengdu through the Sichuan Airlines "tokyo-chengdu" flight, and then through the car ride to Wuhan.

| Korea

South Korea was also one of the main destinations outside Wuhan before the city's closure, with two new cases of pneumonia confirmed.

South Korea has confirmed its fourth case of COVID-19 pneumonia, the Ministry of Disease Management announced on Sunday, and announced it would step up quarantine and expand the scope of health questionnaires from travellers from Wuhan to travellers from all over China.

The first finance reporter contacted the South Korean Department of Disease Management, which is similar to China's Center for Disease Control and Prevention. The other side said that there is no plan to repatriate Wuhan tourists or ban them from entering the country for the time being, but that they are currently at the South Korean airport, all visitors from China are required to fill out a health questionnaire and take two temperature checks. In addition, the number of airport disinfections has doubled, and public facilities such as escalators, public telephones and drinking fountains are disinfected twice a day.

The person in charge further said that through cooperation with the Immigration Department, information on all persons entering from Wuhan has been sent to the South Korean medical management system, and when these persons go to the hospital for medical treatment, the hospital system will immediately alert the population from or Transit Wuhan area, and as long as there is a new type of pneumonia may appear any symptoms, should immediately report to the CDC for management.

Notably, while South Korea has said it has no plans to impose restrictions on Chinese tourists, the Consulate General of South Korea, Wuhan has said it will stop accepting visas because of pressure from other businesses, such as evacuating overseas Chinese, the Korean Doctors Association also issued a statement calling on the government to conduct a thorough investigation, follow-up and management of all visitors from China, and urged the government to stop the general operation of community health centers, in favor of a comprehensive response to the new pneumonia.

South Korean President Moon jae-in also instructed the Disease Control Agency to work with the Immigration Agency to screen more than 100 tourists from the Wuhan area for the virus after the outbreak, and to quarantine themselves until the results were updated.

According to preliminary statistics from the Seoul Metropolitan Government, 70 percent of the Chinese tourists in South Korea are individual tourists who are not part of tour groups, which poses a huge challenge to tourist management.

First Business reporter contacted a Wuhan based tourist, Miss Sun, who is still traveling in South Korea. She told the reporter that the Korean Air flight she was on when she arrived had been suspended and she had received contact from Korean Airlines, you can change it to any destination in China, you can pay the difference, and you can choose to return the ticket free of charge.

"In addition, when my hotel learned that I was from Wuhan, it also requested to be able to leave as soon as possible and report to the CDC, " said Ms. Sun, who said she was already planning to leave South Korea early, and travel to the cities where targeted accommodation is available to await further information.

According to information provided by the CTRIP, the airline's website and Seoul Incheon airport, both China Southern Airlines and Korean Air Lines are currently operating the wuhan-seoul route, and both have announced plans to suspend and change the Wuhan route, korean airlines such as Korean Air and Asiana Airlines have introduced special refund measures for flights departing or arriving in China from January 20 to February 29, major local hotel chains such as Lotte in South Korea and Silla have also introduced special measures to allow Chinese tourists to change or cancel their bookings free of charge.
